<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1930,2034]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,152,294]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,1930,1956]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion:</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[356,460,1930,1956]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">holotype</typeStatus>
male and only specimen on which this taxon is based, is lost, and the species has not been found again since its first description from the Bohemian mountains. The original description poses several important open questions: (
<number box="[577,590,2008,2034]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
) palps insert parallel to each other or rotated to an oblique-horizontal position? (
<number box="[283,300,152,178]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="2.0">2</number>
) Is there a glandular pore on Cx-III (the statement &quot;all [coxal] plates without any setation&quot; suggests that the specimen was badly damaged or insufficiently observed)? (
<number box="[1107,1123,190,216]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="3.0">3</number>
) Are there dorsal muscle insertion sclerites? As these and other important questions cannot be answered in the absence of the 
<typeStatus box="[1326,1432,229,255]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">holotype</typeStatus>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,260,268,293]" class="Arachnida" family="Sperchonidae" genus="Sperchon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hystrix">
<emphasis box="[151,260,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">S. hystrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
must be considered a 
<emphasis box="[521,696,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
species 
<taxonomicName box="[613,696,268,293]" class="Arachnida" family="Hydryphantidae" genus="Todothyas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incerta">incerta</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
